node.text: Photo by @veronika_k_ko / This is Nur, and one of her favorite activities is to play peekaboo with me or with the other animals at my home. I have adopted a few cats and a dog that were once abandoned, lonely, hungry, and even without a chance to live. But now they are happy, smiling, and grateful creatures. We give each other endless love. If you want to have a faithful and lovely friend, and have fun and joy at home, please adopt an animal from a shelter. Let's open our hearts and do a good deed to save a life. The animals deserve it; they are our little brothers and sisters with whom we share the Earth! #YourShotPhotographer #cat #animals #adoptanimals #catportrait

node.text: Photo by Michel Godimus @yosomono.photography / A red deer sticks its head out of the ferns. This breed of deer can have very impressive antlers! In this photo, the antlers are growing and still covered with a skin; we call this the velvet antler. #YourShotPhotographer #Deer

node.text: Photo by @karimiliya / Sometimes the best photographic opportunities come from unexpected places without having to go far out of your way. While waiting to board a ferry, I saw an arctic tern flying above these grasses with the setting sun behind it. I ran over and spent a few minutes trying to get a photo until I had to run back before the ferry left without me. #YourShotPhotographer

node.text: Photo by @doug_gimesy / Middle-earth? / No, this is Enderby Island, about 465 kilometers (290 miles) south of the South Island of New Zealand. Dominant vegetation here includes rata forest and megaherbs such as the Campbell Island carrot, a large and robust perennial herb that can grow up to two meters (6.5 feet) in height. The island is significant as a breeding site for several species of seabirds as well as the endemic Auckland shag, Auckland teal, Auckland rail, and Auckland snipe. Other fauna found here include the brown skua, New Zealand pipit, New Zealand sea lion, northern giant petrel, and yellow-eyed penguin. #YourShotPhotographer #middleearth #enderbyisland #forest

node.text: Photo by @gretchenkaystuart / A brown pelican stretches its pouch with a bill throw. Brown pelicans were once threatened with extinction due to pesticide pollution, but today they are thriving in coastal habitats in the southern United States. I captured this photo with a 400mm zoom in the Florida Panhandle. #brownpelican #YourShotPhotographer
